Reasoning: 
1. cs.GT (Game Theory): The paper is primarily focused on studying the performance of two pivoting algorithms on linear complementarity problems that arise from infinite games, such as parity, average-reward, and discounted games. Therefore, it is highly likely that this paper belongs to the Game Theory sub-category.
2. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms): The paper discusses two algorithms and their performance on linear complementarity problems. This makes it relevant to the Data Structures and Algorithms sub-category.
3. cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence): The paper deals with algorithms that are used in solving games, which is a common application of artificial intelligence. Therefore, it is possible that this paper belongs to the Artificial Intelligence sub-category.
4. cs.LG (Machine Learning): Although the paper does not explicitly mention machine learning, the algorithms discussed in the paper can be seen as optimization algorithms, which are often used in machine learning. Therefore, it is possible that this paper belongs to the Machine Learning sub-category.
5. cs.CC (Computational Complexity): The paper discusses the worst-case performance of the two algorithms on a family of parity games, indicating that they perform no better for parity, average-reward, or discounted games than they do for general P-matrix LCPs. This makes it relevant to the Computational Complexity sub-category.
